<li>Make <code>posts</code> dir inside <code>content</code> subdir if not already their.</li>
</ol>
<div class="highlight"><pre tabindex="0" style="color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;"><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash"><span style="display:flex;"><span>mkdir content/posts 
</span></span></code></pre></div><ol start="3">
<li>Sync your obsidian posts folder to content/posts folder. We will use rsync for it.</li>
</ol>
<div class="highlight"><pre tabindex="0" style="color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;"><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash"><span style="display:flex;"><span>rsync -av --delete ~/vault/posts ~/hugo-test-blog/content/posts
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span><span style="color:#75715e"># source path is where you created your posts dir for obsidian</span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span><span style="color:#75715e"># destination path is ..../hugo-test-blog/content/posts</span>
</span></span></code></pre></div><ol start="4">
<li>Done! Go to <code>posts</code> in your website and you will see the latest post.</li>
</ol>
